## Algorithm Design: Closed-Form NP Energy Detector with Vectorized Monte Carlo Validation
Type: closed_form — Compute analytic NP thresholds and theoretical \(P_d\), then validate with vectorized Monte Carlo and ROC generation under ideal and noise-mismatch settings.

### Step-by-step implementation (each step must appear in algorithm_core):
**Step 1: Initialize constants and grids**
  - Description: Set fixed task parameters and convert SNR dB grid to linear values for all subsequent computations.
  - Formula: $N=256,\;\alpha=0.01,\;\mathcal{G}_{\mathrm{dB}}=\{-20,-18,\dots,0\},\;\gamma_i=10^{\mathcal{G}_{\mathrm{dB}}[i]/10},\;i=1,\dots,11,\;T=100000$
  - Inputs: task configuration
  - Outputs: N, alpha, gamma_grid, T
  - numpy/scipy hint: `Use np.array for dB grid and gamma_grid = 10**(snr_db/10).`
**Step 2: Set random seed and noise variance reference**
  - Description: Fix reproducibility and define assumed noise variance used in normalization and thresholding.
  - Formula: $\text{seed}=2026,\;\sigma_{w,\mathrm{assumed}}^2>0\;\text{(fixed reference)},\;\Delta_{\nu}\in\{-1,0,1\}\;\text{dB}$
  - Inputs: random_seed, sigma_w2_assumed, noise_power_mismatch_db
  - Outputs: rng_state, sigma_w2_assumed, mismatch_grid
  - numpy/scipy hint: `Use np.random.default_rng(seed).`
**Step 3: Compute NP thresholds for required Pfa points**
  - Description: Obtain analytic thresholds from central chi-square quantiles for the fixed and ROC operating points.
  - Formula: $\eta(\alpha_m)=\frac{1}{2}F^{-1}_{\chi^2_{2N}}(1-\alpha_m),\;\alpha_m\in\{0.01,0.05,0.1\}$
  - Inputs: N, pfa_points
  - Outputs: eta_map
  - numpy/scipy hint: `Use scipy.stats.chi2.ppf(1-alpha_m, df=2*N)/2.`
**Step 4: Compute theoretical Pd curves**
  - Description: Evaluate closed-form \(P_d\) over SNR for each fixed \(P_{fa}\) threshold.
  - Formula: $P_d^{\mathrm{th}}(\gamma_i;\alpha_m)=1-F_{\chi^2_{2N}}\!\left(\frac{2\eta(\alpha_m)}{1+\gamma_i}\right),\;i=1,\dots,11$
  - Inputs: gamma_grid, eta_map, N
  - Outputs: pd_theory
  - numpy/scipy hint: `Use scipy.stats.chi2.cdf with vectorized broadcasting.`
**Step 5: Generate H0 Monte Carlo samples**
  - Description: Create \(T\times N\) i.i.d. complex Gaussian noise matrices for each mismatch scenario.
  - Formula: $w_{t,n}^{(\delta)}=\sqrt{\frac{\sigma_{w,\mathrm{true}}^2(\delta)}{2}}\left(a_{t,n}+j b_{t,n}\right),\;a_{t,n},b_{t,n}\overset{i.i.d.}{\sim}\mathcal{N}(0,1),\;\sigma_{w,\mathrm{true}}^2(\delta)=\sigma_{w,\mathrm{assumed}}^2\cdot10^{\delta/10}$
  - Inputs: T, N, sigma_w2_assumed, mismatch_grid, rng_state
  - Outputs: W_delta
  - numpy/scipy hint: `Use rng.standard_normal((T,N)) for real and imag parts, then combine.`
**Step 6: Generate H1 Monte Carlo samples per SNR**
  - Description: For each SNR and mismatch case, generate Gaussian signal plus noise observations.
  - Formula: $s_{t,n}^{(i,\delta)}=\sqrt{\frac{\gamma_i\sigma_{w,\mathrm{true}}^2(\delta)}{2}}\left(c_{t,n}+j d_{t,n}\right),\;y_{t,n}^{(1,i,\delta)}=s_{t,n}^{(i,\delta)}+w_{t,n}^{(\delta)}$
  - Inputs: gamma_grid, W_delta, sigma_w2_assumed, mismatch_grid, rng_state
  - Outputs: Y1_i_delta
  - numpy/scipy hint: `Vectorize over trials and samples; loop only over SNR points.`
**Step 7: Compute normalized energy statistics**
  - Description: Reduce raw complex samples to scalar sufficient statistics for H0 and H1.
  - Formula: $U_t^{(0,\delta)}=\frac{1}{\sigma_{w,\mathrm{assumed}}^2}\sum_{n=1}^{N}\left|w_{t,n}^{(\delta)}\right|^2,\quad U_t^{(1,i,\delta)}=\frac{1}{\sigma_{w,\mathrm{assumed}}^2}\sum_{n=1}^{N}\left|y_{t,n}^{(1,i,\delta)}\right|^2$
  - Inputs: W_delta, Y1_i_delta, sigma_w2_assumed
  - Outputs: U0_delta, U1_i_delta
  - numpy/scipy hint: `Use np.abs(X)**2 then np.sum(axis=1).`
**Step 8: Apply NP decision rule**
  - Description: Threshold statistics to produce binary decisions under each hypothesis.
  - Formula: $d_t^{(0,\delta,\alpha_m)}=\mathbb{1}\{U_t^{(0,\delta)}>\eta(\alpha_m)\},\quad d_t^{(1,i,\delta,\alpha_m)}=\mathbb{1}\{U_t^{(1,i,\delta)}>\eta(\alpha_m)\}$
  - Inputs: U0_delta, U1_i_delta, eta_map
  - Outputs: D0, D1
  - numpy/scipy hint: `Use boolean comparisons and astype(np.float64) for averaging.`
**Step 9: Estimate empirical Pfa and Pd**
  - Description: Compute Monte Carlo probabilities and theory-simulation gaps for reporting targets.
  - Formula: $\widehat{P}_{fa}(\delta,\alpha_m)=\frac{1}{T}\sum_{t=1}^{T}d_t^{(0,\delta,\alpha_m)},\quad \widehat{P}_{d}(i,\delta,\alpha_m)=\frac{1}{T}\sum_{t=1}^{T}d_t^{(1,i,\delta,\alpha_m)},\quad \Delta_{pd}(i)=\left|\widehat{P}_{d}(i,0,0.01)-P_d^{\mathrm{th}}(\gamma_i;0.01)\right|$
  - Inputs: D0, D1, pd_theory
  - Outputs: pfa_emp, pd_emp, pd_gap
  - numpy/scipy hint: `Use np.mean over trial axis and np.abs difference.`
**Step 10: Generate full ROC and AUC**
  - Description: Sweep threshold grid to compute ROC points and numerical AUC at selected SNR values.
  - Formula: $\eta_r\in\mathcal{E},\;P_{fa,r}=\frac{1}{T}\sum_{t=1}^{T}\mathbb{1}\{U_t^{(0,0)}>\eta_r\},\;P_{d,r}(i)=\frac{1}{T}\sum_{t=1}^{T}\mathbb{1}\{U_t^{(1,i,0)}>\eta_r\},\;\mathrm{AUC}(i)=\int_{0}^{1}P_d(P_{fa};i)\,dP_{fa}$
  - Inputs: U0_delta, U1_i_delta, roc_threshold_grid
  - Outputs: roc_curves, auc_values
  - numpy/scipy hint: `Use np.quantile for threshold grid, vectorized comparisons, and np.trapz for AUC.`
**Step 11: Measure runtime and operation count**
  - Description: Compute per-interval runtime and analytical operation complexity for the primary detector.
  - Formula: $\text{runtime\_ms\_per\_interval}=1000\cdot\frac{t_{\mathrm{end}}-t_{\mathrm{start}}}{N_{\mathrm{intervals}}},\quad \mathrm{ops}_{\mathrm{ED}}\approx c\,N\;\Rightarrow\;\mathcal{O}(N)$
  - Inputs: timing_marks, N, num_intervals_processed
  - Outputs: runtime_ms_per_interval, complexity_ops_per_interval
  - numpy/scipy hint: `Use time.perf_counter and simple scalar arithmetic.`

### Complexity: Primary detector evaluation is O(N) per interval; full study cost is O(|SNR|·T·N) for Monte Carlo sweeps. — dominant: Accumulation of squared magnitudes for energy statistics over T×N samples (and threshold sweeps for ROC).

